## Copy vs update (important)

- **Generate** a new project: `copier copy TEMPLATE DESTINATION`.
- **Update** an existing generated project to the latest template version: `copier update`.
- **`copier recopy`**: full re-application with saved answers; no smart merge — prefer **`copier update`** for routine sync.

For updates, Copier works best when:

1. The template includes a valid `.copier-answers.yml` file.
2. The template is versioned with git tags (PEP 440).
3. The destination folder is versioned with git.

Use **`copier update --trust`** if the template runs tasks. **`--defaults`**, **`--data`**, **`--data-file`**, and
**`--vcs-ref=:current:`** behave as in Copier’s updating docs. **`copier check-update`** reports newer template
versions (JSON and exit codes with **`--quiet`** for scripts).

Template **`_tasks`** typically run on both copy and update unless you pass **`--skip-tasks`**.

### Never edit `.copier-answers.yml` by hand

Do not manually change the answers file (`.copier-answers.yml`, controlled by `_answers_file` in
`copier.yml`). The update algorithm relies on it and manual edits can lead to unpredictable diffs.

### Handle update conflicts

**`--conflict inline`** (default) embeds markers in files; **`--conflict rej`** writes **`*.rej`** files.
Pre-commit here covers both cases. Prefer SSH or credential-free template URLs so secrets do not land in
`.copier-answers.yml`.

## Standards enforcement

Standards are enforced at three layers — during development via Claude hooks, at commit via pre-commit, and in CI via GitHub Actions.

### Tooling layer (always active)

| What | Tool | When |
|---|---|---|
| Lint + style | ruff | `just lint` / pre-commit / CI |
| Docstrings | ruff `D` rules (Google) | `just docs-check` / CI |
| Complexity | ruff `C90` (max 10) | `just lint` |
| Performance | ruff `PERF` | `just lint` |
| Types | basedpyright strict | `just type` / pre-commit / CI |
| Test coverage | pytest-cov (≥ 85 %) | `just coverage` / CI |

### Claude commands (on-demand workflows)

| Slash command | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `/review` | Full pre-merge checklist: lint + types + docstrings + test coverage + symbol scan |
| `/coverage` | Run coverage, identify gaps below 85 %, write missing tests |
| `/docs-check` | Audit and repair Google-style docstrings across all source files |
| `/standards` | Consolidated pass/fail report — the "ready to merge?" gate |

### Claude hooks (automatic feedback)

A **PostToolUse hook** fires after every Python file edit during a Claude session:
- Runs ruff check + basedpyright on the edited file
- Surfaces violations back to Claude so it can self-correct in the same turn

### Definition of done

A feature or fix is **done** when all of the following are true:

1. `just ci` passes with zero errors (lint → types → docstrings → tests → pre-commit).
2. Every new public function/class/method has a Google-style docstring (Args/Returns/Raises where applicable).
3. Every new function/method has complete type annotations (parameters + return type).
4. At least one test case covers each new public symbol.
5. `just coverage` reports no module below 85 %.
6. No `TODO` or `FIXME` comments are left in modified files (unless tracked as issues).

## Package structure

Source code lives under `src/{{ package_name }}/`.
Tests live under `tests/`.
The `.claude/` directory holds Claude Code slash-command prompts and PostToolUse hooks for local standards enforcement.

## Code style

- Line length: 100 characters
- Python {{ python_min_version }}+
- Ruff rules: `E`, `F`, `I`, `UP`, `B`, `SIM`, `C4`, `RUF`, `TCH`, `PGH`, `PT`, `ARG`, `D`, `C90`, `PERF`.
  Rule `E501` is ignored (handled by the formatter). Test files are exempt from `D` and `ARG`.
- Docstring convention: **Google style** (enforced by ruff `D` rules + `pydocstyle.convention = "google"`).
- McCabe complexity: max 10 per function.
- Type annotations required on all public functions and methods (basedpyright strict mode).
